TY  - JOUR
T1  - Integrating Acquired Capabilities: When Structural Integration Is (Un)necessary
AU  - Puranam, Phanish
AU  - Singh, Harbir
AU  - Chaudhuri, Saikat
Y1  - 2009/03/06
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1090.0422
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1090.0422
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 313
EP  - 328
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Acquirers who buy small technology-based firms for their technological capabilities often discover that postmerger integration can destroy the very innovative capabilities that made the acquired organization attractive in the first place. Viewing structural integration as a mechanism to achieve coordination between acquirer and target organizations helps explain why structural integration may be necessary in technology acquisitions despite the costs of disruption this imposes, as well as the conditions under which it becomes less (or un-) necessary. We show that interdependence motivates structural integration but that preexisting common ground offers acquirers an alternate path to achieving coordination, which may be less disruptive than structural integration.
AB  - Acquirers who buy small technology-based firms for their technological capabilities often discover that postmerger integration can destroy the very innovative capabilities that made the acquired organization attractive in the first place. Viewing structural integration as a mechanism to achieve coordination between acquirer and target organizations helps explain why structural integration may be necessary in technology acquisitions despite the costs of disruption this imposes, as well as the conditions under which it becomes less (or un-) necessary. We show that interdependence motivates structural integration but that preexisting common ground offers acquirers an alternate path to achieving coordination, which may be less disruptive than structural integration.
